Great Southern White Ascia monuste butterflies are abundant along the roadside and in fields in southern Florida and other extremely southern states of the United States.
The orange antennae-tips show in this head shot.
They look so cute with their little "ears" at this stage. Those are actually developing stinkhorns. They're just tiny buds at this stage, but get longer with each subsequent instar.

They all tend to congregate at the tip of the plant, fighting over the youngest leaves. I tried several times to separate them and put each on their own leaf, but they just crawled back up and started brawling again. Silly little bugs! There's plenty of milkweed for everyone.
Third instar monarch caterpillar.

Second instar (left) and two already much larger third instars. They like to crawl up to the shoot tip to chew on the youngest leaves. They're quite competitive, too, fighting with each other when they happen to meet on the same leaf. I never realized caterpillars could be so aggressive!

Freshly molted fourth instar, with the shed skin it crawled out of behind it and the new exoskeleton still hardening and developing its black stripes on the face. It looked like it was pausing to say a prayer. They sit still for a while before and after molting and are very fragile at this stage, so it's best not to disturb them.

They do like the flowers, too, especially the young buds. My fourth instar caterpillars seem to all congregate in the flowers buds. I guess pollen and nectar makes for a very tasty and nutritious meal, even for caterpillars.

After molting, they'll turn around and eat their old skin. No need to let all that good caterpillar protein go to waste! This one did just that and is ready to head off and gorge on more milkweed again.

Fourth instars investigating the new batch of milkweed seedlings I gave them and promptly heading straight up for the youngest leaves again. Those surely must taste the best! All my "used" milkweed seedlings have been decapitated. I'm sure they'll recover just fine; they're already sending up lateral shoots. The early instar feeder plants got off easy - these plants hosting the much bigger hungry fourth instar probably aren't going to fare as well.

Another one molting! They will sit very still for a while before they go through this process, so having a caterpillar stop eating and sitting still is not necessarily a sign that they're sick. They probably are just growing a new skin and preparing to shed the old one. It's best not to disturb them during this process.
Third instar on top of the leaf, fourth instar below. Yes, they do grow up fast! The fifth instar will again be twice as long as the fourth instar. They're quickly becoming big bugs!
They really do love those flower buds, at least once they've grown big like this.

Here's my set up for the caterpillars. At this stage I had three potted milkweed seedlings and a vase with a flowering stalk cut from a mature plant inside a large pop-up butterfly cage. It has one clear side (through which I took the picture) and mesh on all other sides for ventilation. I have a number of seedlings planted that I'll rotate in for fresh food and more mature plants to cut for the later instars. The paper towels are for catching the frass (aka caterpillar poop) for easier cleaning between changing out pots.
The sad remains of what used to be a budding milkweed inflorescence. Those buds sure must be tasty!

Fifth instar shortly after molting - final stage as caterpillar! This one was 3 cm long when I took the picture. You can tell it is the fifth instar from the length of the tentacles and the distinctive white spots on the prolegs.

The big ones appear to be chewing even through the night, skipping sleep in favor of eating and pooping and growing as much as possible. They have the habit of cutting the midrib, causing the leaf to fold down, and then hiding underneath and eating it from the tip (now at the bottom) up.

Fifth instar back to munching on the next batch of yummy buds. This is the "big bug" of the bunch and probably going to be the first one to form a chrysalis. By now about half of them have molted into the fifth instar stage, but I also still have a few small third instars.

Early second instar, I presume, just a few millimeters long. This was how most of the caterpillars looked like that I received, with a few much smaller ones with less prominent stripes (if any) that I assume were first instar but missed to take a picture of.

The small heath  (Coenonympha pamphilus) is a butterfly species belonging to the family Nymphalidae, (subfamily Satyrinae, commonly known as "the browns"). It is widespread in Eurasia and northwestern Africa, preferring drier habitats than other Coenonymphae. The larval host plants are grasses, notably sheep's fescue and rough meadow grass.
Great Spangled Fritillary feeding on Common Milkweed in front of the Daniel Boone Native Gardens.
Purple Coneflower with visitor.

Sympetrum is a genus of small to medium-sized skimmer dragonflies, known as darters in the UK and as meadowhawks in the North America. The more than 50 species predominantly live in the temperate zone of the Northern Hemisphere.

The blue dasher (Pachydiplax longipennis) is a dragonfly of the skimmer family. It is common and widely distributed in the United States.
Mature males develop a bluish-white pruinescence on the back of the abdomen and, in western individuals, on the thorax. They display this pruinescence to other males as a threat while defending territories at the edge of the water.

The Tropical Checkered Skipper (Pyrgus oileus) grows to about 1 1/4 inch and is slaty brown when viewed above, with numerous creamy colored spots. The male has conspicuous bluish-gray hair-like scales. When it is viewed from below, it is tan with dark brown and gray spots that are outlined in black. It is commonly seen in open areas and feeds on Mallows and Hollyhock.

Females show some differences compared with males. The general rule is that the wings of the male are darker than on the females. In mainland males, the length of the femur, the longest leg section, varies; they also have longer front and shorter hind wings than the females. The island representatives, however, have the front and hind wings longer than the female, and the femur is the same for both sexes. There are other differences between mainland and island specimens, particularly in terms of coloring. Island representatives are generally darker.
